#: ../../doc/contributing/docs/style.rst:8
msgid "Concise is good"
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc/contributing/docs/style.rst:10
msgid "People usually read technical documentation because they want something up and running quickly. Write simpler, more concise sentences."
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc/contributing/docs/style.rst:13
msgid "Split the content into smaller paragraphs to improve readability. This will also eliminate the need for using ``|br|`` and help us translate content faster. Any paragraph over 6 sentences is large."
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc/contributing/docs/style.rst:18
msgid "Keep your audience in mind"
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc/contributing/docs/style.rst:20
msgid "Consider your audience's level. A getting started guide should be written in simpler terms than an advanced internals description."
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc/contributing/docs/style.rst:23
msgid "If you choose to use metaphors to clarify a concept, make sure they are relatable for an international audience of IT professionals."
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc/contributing/docs/style.rst:27
msgid "Don't say \"we\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc/contributing/docs/style.rst:29
msgid "Only use the pronoun \"we\" in entry-level texts like getting started guides. In other cases, avoid using \"we\", because it is unclear who that is exactly. `Consider how Gentoo does it <https://wiki.gentoo.org/wiki/Gentoo_Wiki:Guidelines#Avoid_first_and_second_person_writing>`__."
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc/contributing/docs/style.rst:34
msgid "Stick to the facts"
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc/contributing/docs/style.rst:36
msgid "Use measurable facts instead of personal judgments. Different users may have different ideas of what \"often\", \"slow\", or \"small\" means."
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc/contributing/docs/style.rst:39
msgid "**Bad example:** This parameter is rarely updated."
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc/contributing/docs/style.rst:41
msgid "**Good example:** This parameter is updated every two hours or more rarely."
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc/contributing/docs/style.rst:44
msgid "Refer to absolute time"
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc/contributing/docs/style.rst:46
msgid "Temporal adverbs like \"today\", \"currently\", \"now\", \"in the future\", etc. are relative -- that is, they are based on the time the documentation is created."
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc/contributing/docs/style.rst:49
msgid "Instead of these words, use absolute terms like version numbers or years. The meaning of those terms doesn't change over time."
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc/contributing/docs/style.rst:52
msgid "If technical documentation is tied semantically to the time it was created, it increases the risk of the documentation becoming obsolete."
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc/contributing/docs/style.rst:55
msgid "**Bad example:** Previously, the functionality worked differently. Currently, it supports SSL."
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc/contributing/docs/style.rst:58
msgid "**Good example:** Before version x.y.z, the functionality worked differently. Since version x.y.z, it supports SSL."
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc/contributing/docs/style.rst:62
msgid "Express one idea in a sentence"
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc/contributing/docs/style.rst:64
msgid "Say exactly one thing in a sentence. If you want to define or clarify something, do it in a separate sentence. Simple sentences are easier to read, understand and translate."
msgstr ""

